values
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:learn:1c905a15', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How is recurrence used to model money and populations?", "reading": "<p>Recurrence relationships model any quantity that changes by the <strong>same factor</strong> each period — the classic case is <strong>compound interest</strong>.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li><strong>Growth of \\( r\\% \\) per period</strong> → multiply by \\( \\left(1 + \\frac{r}{100}\\right) \\). So \\( 3\\% \\) interest gives \\( x_{n+1} = 1.03\\,x_n \\).</li>\n              <li><strong>Depreciation / decay of \\( r\\% \\)</strong> → multiply by \\( \\left(1 - \\frac{r}{100}\\right) \\). So losing \\( 15\\% \\) a year gives \\( x_{n+1} = 0.85\\,x_n \\).</li>\n              <li><strong>Regular top-up savings</strong> combine both: e.g. \\( x_{n+1} = 1.03\\,x_n + 50 \\) grows the balance by \\( 3\\% \\) and then adds a \\( £50 \\) deposit.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — £500 invested at \\( 3\\% \\) per year, \\( x_1 = 500 \\), \\( x_{n+1} = 1.03\\,x_n \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. \\( x_1 = 500 \\) (the amount invested).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. After 1 year: \\( x_2 = 1.03 \\times 500 = 515 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. After 2 years: \\( x_3 = 1.03 \\times 515 = 530.45 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. After 3 years: \\( x_4 = 1.03 \\times 530.45 = 546.36 \\) (to the nearest penny).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Interest is earned on the interest, so the balance grows a little faster each year.</p>", "question": "A car worth \\( £8000 \\) depreciates by \\( 20\\% \\) each year. Which recurrence models its value?", "options": ["\\( x_{n+1} = 0.8x_n \\)", "\\( x_{n+1} = 1.2x_n \\)", "\\( x_{n+1} = x_n - 20 \\)", "\\( x_{n+1} = 0.2x_n \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Losing \\( 20\\% \\) leaves \\( 80\\% \\), so multiply by \\( 1 - 0.20 = 0.8 \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:misc:85d9672e', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> For \\( x_{n+1} = 5x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 2 \\), writing \\( x_2 = 2 + 5 = 7 \\).</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The rule multiplies, it does not add. A weak answer treats \\( 5x_n \\) as \\( x_n + 5 \\); a strong answer writes \\( x_2 = 5 \\times 2 = 10 \\).</p>", "question": "For \\( x_{n+1} = 5x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 2 \\), what is \\( x_2 \\)?", "options": ["\\( 10 \\)", "\\( 7 \\)", "\\( 25 \\)", "\\( 5 \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x_2 = 5 \\times 2 = 10 \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:misc:e97fabf3', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Trying to generate \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\) from a single starting value.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A second-order rule needs two terms to start. A weak answer stalls with only \\( x_1 \\); a strong answer uses both \\( x_1 \\) and \\( x_2 \\), then builds \\( x_3 = x_2 + x_1 \\).</p>", "question": "How many starting values does \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\) need?", "options": ["Two", "One", "None", "Three"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "It reaches back two terms, so it needs the first two terms."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:misc:d59cdd12', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Doing the whole iteration on the calculator and writing down only the final answer.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Examiners award a mark for each correct term, so unshown working can lose marks after a slip. A weak answer shows nothing; a strong answer sets each line out formally: \\( x_3 = \\dots,\\ x_4 = \\dots,\\ x_5 = \\dots \\). This also guards against a transcription error when copying from the calculator.</p>", "question": "Why set out each term on its own line?", "options": ["Each correct term earns its own mark and it prevents copying slips", "It uses more paper", "It is required by law", "To make the answer look longer"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Every term is worth a mark, and formal working avoids calculator transcription errors."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:misc:b0a14992', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Not recognising the phrase ''recurrence relationship'' and leaving the question blank.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> ''Recurrence relationship'' just means a term-to-term rule — a way of getting the next term from earlier ones. A weak answer gives up on the wording; a strong answer reads the rule and simply substitutes the given values.</p>", "question": "What does ''recurrence relationship'' mean?", "options": ["A rule giving each term from earlier terms", "The sum of all the terms", "The 100th term of the sequence", "A type of graph"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "It is a term-to-term rule — nothing more exotic than substituting into the given formula."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:misc:c8c267c3', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Modelling 3% compound interest with the multiplier \\( 0.03 \\) or \\( 1.3 \\).</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A percentage increase adds to 1, and 3% is \\( 0.03 \\), not \\( 0.3 \\). A weak answer uses \\( 0.03 \\) or \\( 1.3 \\); a strong answer uses \\( 1 + 0.03 = 1.03 \\).</p>", "question": "The multiplier for a 3% yearly increase is:", "options": ["\\( 1.03 \\)", "\\( 0.03 \\)", "\\( 1.3 \\)", "\\( 3 \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 1 + \\frac{3}{100} = 1.03 \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:tips:c498a55d', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Show every term (method marks)", "reading": "<p>On a \"[3]\" recurrence question, each correct term earns <strong>its own mark</strong>. For \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + 2x_n \\), write \\( x_3 \\), \\( x_4 \\) and \\( x_5 \\) on separate lines — a slip then costs one mark, not all three. Doing it all silently on the calculator risks losing the lot to one arithmetic error.</p>", "question": "Why write each term of a recurrence on its own line?", "options": ["Each correct term earns a separate mark", "It is not necessary", "To slow yourself down", "To fill the answer space"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Marks are awarded term by term, so visible correct terms protect your score."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:tips:ab6b6cd3', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — ''Determine'' means value plus working", "reading": "<p>The command word <strong>\"Determine\"</strong> asks for the value <em>supported by working</em> — you must show how you reached it, not just state the final number. For \\( x_5 \\), show the terms you built on the way (\\( x_3 \\), \\( x_4 \\)) so the method is clear.</p>", "question": "What does ''Determine the value of \\( x_5 \\)'' require?", "options": ["The value with working shown", "Only the final number", "A graph of the sequence", "A decimal approximation"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "''Determine'' expects justification — the value backed by visible working."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:tips:ee706019', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Turn a percentage into a multiplier", "reading": "<p>For modelling questions, convert the rate to a multiplier: a rise of \\( r\\% \\) gives \\( \\left(1 + \\frac{r}{100}\\right) \\); a fall of \\( r\\% \\) gives \\( \\left(1 - \\frac{r}{100}\\right) \\). So \\( 3\\% \\) growth is \\( 1.03 \\) and \\( 15\\% \\) depreciation is \\( 0.85 \\). Then the model is simply \\( x_{n+1} = (\\text{multiplier})\\,x_n \\).</p>", "question": "The multiplier for a 7% yearly decrease is:", "options": ["\\( 0.93 \\)", "\\( 1.07 \\)", "\\( 0.07 \\)", "\\( 0.7 \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A fall of 7% leaves 93%, so multiply by \\( 1 - 0.07 = 0.93 \\)."}'::jsonb),
